#: ../../../containers.rst:252
msgid "Configuring the Container Recipe"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:254
msgid ""
"Any Spack Environment can be used for the automatic generation of container "
"recipes. Sensible defaults are provided for things like the base image or "
"the version of Spack used in the image. If a finer tuning is needed it can "
"be obtained by adding the relevant metadata under the ``container`` "
"attribute of environments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:260
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - gromacs+mpi\n"
"  - mpich\n"
"\n"
"  container:\n"
"    # Select the format of the recipe e.g. docker,\n"
"    # singularity or anything else that is currently supported\n"
"    format: docker\n"
"\n"
"    # Sets the base images for the stages where Spack builds the\n"
"    # software or where the software gets installed after being built..\n"
"    images:\n"
"      os: \"centos:7\"\n"
"      spack: develop\n"
"\n"
"    # Whether or not to strip binaries\n"
"    strip: true\n"
"\n"
"    # Additional system packages that are needed at runtime\n"
"    os_packages:\n"
"      final:\n"
"      - libgomp\n"
"\n"
"    # Labels for the image\n"
"    labels:\n"
"      app: \"gromacs\"\n"
"      mpi: \"mpich\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:291
msgid ""
"A detailed description of the options available can be found in the :ref:"
"`container_config_options` section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:295
msgid "Setting Base Images"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:297
msgid ""
"The ``images`` subsection is used to select both the image where Spack "
"builds the software and the image where the built software is installed. "
"This attribute can be set in different ways and which one to use depends on "
"the use case at hand."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:304
msgid "Use Official Spack Images From Dockerhub"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:306
msgid ""
"To generate a recipe that uses an official Docker image from the Spack "
"organization to build the software and the corresponding official OS image "
"to install the built software, all the user has to do is specify:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:310
msgid "An operating system under ``images:os``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:311
msgid "A Spack version under ``images:spack``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:313
msgid ""
"Any combination of these two values that can be mapped to one of the images "
"discussed in :ref:`container_spack_images` is allowed. For instance, the "
"following ``spack.yaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:317
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - gromacs+mpi\n"
"  - mpich\n"
"\n"
"  container:\n"
"    images:\n"
"      os: centos:7\n"
"      spack: 0.15.4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:329
msgid ""
"uses ``spack/centos7:0.15.4``  and ``centos:7`` for the stages where the "
"software is respectively built and installed:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:332
msgid ""
"# Build stage with Spack pre-installed and ready to be used\n"
"FROM spack/centos7:0.15.4 as builder\n"
"\n"
"# What we want to install and how we want to install it\n"
"# is specified in a manifest file (spack.yaml)\n"
"RUN mkdir /opt/spack-environment \\\n"
"&&  (echo \"spack:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  specs:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  - gromacs+mpi\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  - mpich\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  concretizer:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"    unify: true\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  config:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"    install_tree: /opt/software\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  view: /opt/view\") > /opt/spack-environment/spack.yaml\n"
"[ ... ]\n"
"# Bare OS image to run the installed executables\n"
"FROM centos:7\n"
"\n"
"COPY --from=builder /opt/spack-environment /opt/spack-environment\n"
"COPY --from=builder /opt/software /opt/software\n"
"COPY --from=builder /opt/view /opt/view\n"
"COPY --from=builder /etc/profile.d/z10_spack_environment.sh /etc/profile.d/"
"z10_spack_environment.sh\n"
"\n"
"ENTRYPOINT [\"/bin/bash\", \"--rcfile\", \"/etc/profile\", \"-l\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:360
msgid ""
"This is the simplest available method of selecting base images, and we "
"advise to use it whenever possible. There are cases though where using Spack "
"official images is not enough to fit production needs. In these situations "
"users can extend the recipe to start with the bootstrapping of Spack at a "
"certain pinned version or manually select which base image to start from in "
"the recipe, as we'll see next."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:369
msgid "Use a Bootstrap Stage for Spack"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:371
msgid ""
"In some cases users may want to pin the commit sha that is used for Spack, "
"to ensure later reproducibility, or start from a fork of the official Spack "
"repository to try a bugfix or a feature in the early stage of development. "
"This is possible by being just a little more verbose when specifying "
"information about Spack in the ``spack.yaml`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:376
msgid ""
"images:\n"
"  os: amazonlinux:2\n"
"  spack:\n"
"    # URL of the Spack repository to be used in the container image\n"
"    url: <to-use-a-fork>\n"
"    # Either a commit sha, a branch name or a tag\n"
"    ref: <sha/tag/branch>\n"
"    # If true turn a branch name or a tag into the corresponding commit\n"
"    # sha at the time of recipe generation\n"
"    resolve_sha: <true/false>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:389
msgid ""
"``url`` specifies the URL from which to clone Spack and defaults to https://"
"github.com/spack/spack. The ``ref`` attribute can be either a commit sha, a "
"branch name or a tag. The default value in this case is to use the "
"``develop`` branch, but it may change in the future to point to the latest "
"stable release. Finally ``resolve_sha`` transform branch names or tags into "
"the corresponding commit shas at the time of recipe generation, to allow for "
"a greater reproducibility of the results at a later time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:396
msgid ""
"The list of operating systems that can be used to bootstrap Spack can be "
"obtained with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:403
msgid ""
"The ``resolve_sha`` option uses ``git rev-parse`` under the hood and thus it "
"requires to checkout the corresponding Spack repository in a temporary "
"folder before generating the recipe. Recipe generation may take longer when "
"this option is set to true because of this additional step."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:411
msgid "Use Custom Images Provided by Users"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:413
msgid ""
"Consider, as an example, building a production grade image for a CUDA "
"application. The best strategy would probably be to build on top of images "
"provided by the vendor and regard CUDA as an external package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:417
msgid ""
"Spack doesn't currently provide an official image with CUDA configured this "
"way, but users can build it on their own and then configure the environment "
"to explicitly pull it. This requires users to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:421
msgid "Specify the image used to build the software under ``images:build``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:422
msgid ""
"Specify the image used to install the built software under ``images:final``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:424
msgid "A ``spack.yaml`` like the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:426
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - gromacs@2019.4+cuda build_type=Release\n"
"  - mpich\n"
"  - fftw precision=float\n"
"  packages:\n"
"    cuda:\n"
"      buildable: False\n"
"      externals:\n"
"      - spec: cuda%gcc\n"
"        prefix: /usr/local/cuda\n"
"\n"
"  container:\n"
"    images:\n"
"      build: custom/cuda-10.1-ubuntu18.04:latest\n"
"      final: nvidia/cuda:10.1-base-ubuntu18.04"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:445
msgid "produces, for instance, the following ``Dockerfile``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:447
msgid ""
"# Build stage with Spack pre-installed and ready to be used\n"
"FROM custom/cuda-10.1-ubuntu18.04:latest as builder\n"
"\n"
"# What we want to install and how we want to install it\n"
"# is specified in a manifest file (spack.yaml)\n"
"RUN mkdir /opt/spack-environment \\\n"
"&&  (echo \"spack:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  specs:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  - gromacs@2019.4+cuda build_type=Release\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  - mpich\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  - fftw precision=float\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  packages:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"    cuda:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"      buildable: false\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"      externals:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"      - spec: cuda%gcc\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"        prefix: /usr/local/cuda\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  concretizer:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"    unify: true\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  config:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"    install_tree: /opt/software\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  view: /opt/view\") > /opt/spack-environment/spack.yaml\n"
"\n"
"# Install the software, remove unnecessary deps\n"
"RUN cd /opt/spack-environment && spack env activate . && spack install --"
"fail-fast && spack gc -y\n"
"\n"
"# Strip all the binaries\n"
"RUN find -L /opt/view/* -type f -exec readlink -f '{}' \\; | \\\n"
"    xargs file -i | \\\n"
"    grep 'charset=binary' | \\\n"
"    grep 'x-executable\\|x-archive\\|x-sharedlib' | \\\n"
"    awk -F: '{print $1}' | xargs strip -s\n"
"\n"
"# Modifications to the environment that are necessary to run\n"
"RUN cd /opt/spack-environment && \\\n"
"    spack env activate --sh -d . >> /etc/profile.d/z10_spack_environment.sh\n"
"\n"
"# Bare OS image to run the installed executables\n"
"FROM nvidia/cuda:10.1-base-ubuntu18.04\n"
"\n"
"COPY --from=builder /opt/spack-environment /opt/spack-environment\n"
"COPY --from=builder /opt/software /opt/software\n"
"COPY --from=builder /opt/view /opt/view\n"
"COPY --from=builder /etc/profile.d/z10_spack_environment.sh /etc/profile.d/"
"z10_spack_environment.sh\n"
"\n"
"ENTRYPOINT [\"/bin/bash\", \"--rcfile\", \"/etc/profile\", \"-l\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:496
msgid "where the base images for both stages are completely custom."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:498
msgid ""
"This second mode of selection for base images is more flexible than just "
"choosing an operating system and a Spack version, but is also more "
"demanding. Users may need to generate by themselves their base images and "
"it's also their responsibility to ensure that:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:503
msgid ""
"Spack is available in the ``build`` stage and set up correctly to install "
"the required software"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:504
msgid ""
"The artifacts produced in the ``build`` stage can be executed in the "
"``final`` stage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:506
msgid ""
"Therefore we don't recommend its use in cases that can be otherwise covered "
"by the simplified mode shown first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:511
msgid "Singularity Definition Files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:513
msgid ""
"In addition to producing recipes in ``Dockerfile`` format Spack can produce "
"Singularity Definition Files by just changing the value of the ``format`` "
"attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:517
msgid ""
"$ cat spack.yaml\n"
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - hdf5~mpi\n"
"  container:\n"
"    format: singularity\n"
"\n"
"$ spack containerize > hdf5.def\n"
"$ sudo singularity build hdf5.sif hdf5.def"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:529
msgid ""
"The minimum version of Singularity required to build a SIF (Singularity "
"Image Format) image from the recipes generated by Spack is ``3.5.3``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:534
msgid "Extending the Jinja2 Templates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:536
msgid ""
"The Dockerfile and the Singularity definition file that Spack can generate "
"are based on a few Jinja2 templates that are rendered according to the "
"environment being containerized. Even though Spack allows a great deal of "
"customization by just setting appropriate values for the configuration "
"options, sometimes that is not enough."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:541
msgid ""
"In those cases, a user can directly extend the template that Spack uses to "
"render the image to e.g. set additional environment variables or perform "
"specific operations either before or after a given stage of the build. Let's "
"consider as an example the following structure:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:545
msgid ""
"$ tree /opt/environment\n"
"/opt/environment\n"
"├── data\n"
"│     └── data.csv\n"
"├── spack.yaml\n"
"├── data\n"
"└── templates\n"
"    └── container\n"
"        └── CustomDockerfile"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:557
msgid ""
"containing both the custom template extension and the environment manifest "
"file. To use a custom template, the environment must register the directory "
"containing it, and declare its use under the ``container`` configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:561
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - hdf5~mpi\n"
"  concretizer:\n"
"    unify: true\n"
"  config:\n"
"    template_dirs:\n"
"    - /opt/environment/templates\n"
"  container:\n"
"    format: docker\n"
"    depfile: true\n"
"    template: container/CustomDockerfile"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:577
msgid ""
"The template extension can override two blocks, named ``build_stage`` and "
"``final_stage``, similarly to the example below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:580
msgid ""
"{% extends \"container/Dockerfile\" %}\n"
"{% block build_stage %}\n"
"RUN echo \"Start building\"\n"
"{{ super() }}\n"
"{% endblock %}\n"
"{% block final_stage %}\n"
"{{ super() }}\n"
"COPY data /share/myapp/data\n"
"{% endblock %}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:593
msgid "The Dockerfile is generated by running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:595
msgid "$ spack -e /opt/environment containerize"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:599
msgid ""
"Note that the environment must be active for spack to read the template. The "
"recipe that gets generated contains the two extra instruction that we added "
"in our template extension:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../containers.rst:602
msgid ""
"# Build stage with Spack pre-installed and ready to be used\n"
"FROM spack/ubuntu-jammy:latest as builder\n"
"\n"
"RUN echo \"Start building\"\n"
"\n"
"# What we want to install and how we want to install it\n"
"# is specified in a manifest file (spack.yaml)\n"
"RUN mkdir /opt/spack-environment \\\n"
"&&  (echo \"spack:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  specs:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  - hdf5~mpi\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  concretizer:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"    unify: true\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  config:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"    template_dirs:\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"    - /tmp/environment/templates\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"    install_tree: /opt/software\" \\\n"
"&&   echo \"  view: /opt/view\") > /opt/spack-environment/spack.yaml\n"
"\n"
"# Install the software, remove unnecessary deps\n"
"RUN cd /opt/spack-environment && spack env activate . && spack concretize && "
"spack env depfile -o Makefile && make -j $(nproc) && spack gc -y\n"
"\n"
"# Strip all the binaries\n"
"RUN find -L /opt/view/* -type f -exec readlink -f '{}' \\; | \\\n"
"    xargs file -i | \\\n"
"    grep 'charset=binary' | \\\n"
"    grep 'x-executable\\|x-archive\\|x-sharedlib' | \\\n"
"    awk -F: '{print $1}' | xargs strip -s\n"
"\n"
"# Modifications to the environment that are necessary to run\n"
"RUN cd /opt/spack-environment && \\\n"
"    spack env activate --sh -d . >> /etc/profile.d/z10_spack_environment.sh\n"
"\n"
"# Bare OS image to run the installed executables\n"
"FROM ubuntu:22.04\n"
"\n"
"COPY --from=builder /opt/spack-environment /opt/spack-environment\n"
"COPY --from=builder /opt/software /opt/software\n"
"COPY --from=builder /opt/._view /opt/._view\n"
"COPY --from=builder /opt/view /opt/view\n"
"COPY --from=builder /etc/profile.d/z10_spack_environment.sh /etc/profile.d/"
"z10_spack_environment.sh\n"
"\n"
"COPY data /share/myapp/data\n"
"\n"
"ENTRYPOINT [\"/bin/bash\", \"--rcfile\", \"/etc/profile\", \"-l\", \"-c\", "
"\"$*\", \"--\" ]\n"
"CMD [ \"/bin/bash\" ]"
msgstr ""

